Pages = {{1-10}},
Month = {{JAN}},
Abstract = {{The sunk cost effect, an interesting and well-known decision bias, is
   pervasive in real life and has been studied in various disciplines. In
   this study, we modified a task exemplifying the sunk cost effect and
   used it to evaluate this behavior in individuals with autism spectrum
   disorder (ASD). The control group exhibited a typical sunk cost effect
   in our task. We found that the sunk cost effect was lower in the ASD
   group than in the control group. The results agree with previous
   evidence of reduced sensitivity to context stimuli in individuals with
   ASD and extend this finding to the context of the sunk cost effect. Our
   findings are useful in addressing the practical implications on their
   socioeconomic behavior.}},
