Month = {{NOV}},
Abstract = {{The ability to coordinate our behaviors with those of others is crucial
   for our success as individuals and groups. There are many forms of
   interpersonal coordination where a group of individuals need to
   coordinate their attention, actions, minds, or speech to achieve a
   mutual goal. In the present paper, we review previous hyperscanning
   research on the neural mechanisms underlying a variety of interpersonal
   coordination. Then we highlight how social and cultural factors modulate
   the interbrain mechanisms of interpersonal coordination. Finally, we
   conclude with a discussion of exciting future directions that await
   investigation from a cultural neuroscience perspective.}},
